      content: "<strong>JavaScript-Rendered Content:</strong> Many modern sites render content client-side. Simple HTTP fetches miss this. Use headless browsers: <br/>```typescript<br/>const page = await browser.newPage();<br/>await page.goto(url, { waitUntil: 'networkidle2' });\n// Wait for specific elements if needed\nawait page.waitForSelector('[data-price]', { timeout: 5000 });\nconst content = await page.content();\n```<br/>The `waitUntil: 'networkidle2'` parameter ensures all network requests complete before returning. <strong>Authentication:</strong> Some sites require login. Store credentials securely and login before checking:<br/>```typescript\nawait page.goto('https://site.com/login');\nawait page.type('[name=email]', process.env.EMAIL);\nawait page.type('[name=password]', process.env.PASSWORD);\nawait page.click('[type=submit]');\nawait page.waitForNavigation();\n// Now fetch authenticated page\n```<br/>Use AWS Secrets Manager or HashiCorp Vault to store credentials securely. <strong>Rate Limiting & Politeness:</strong> Checking 10,000+ pages means high request volume. Respect site rate limits: add delays between requests, randomize user agents, rotate IPs if possible. <strong>Many sites block aggressive crawlers.</strong> <strong>Timeouts & Error Handling:</strong> Page loads can hang. Always set timeouts:<br/>```typescript\nawait page.goto(url, { timeout: 30000, waitUntil: 'networkidle2' })\n  .catch(err => {\n    logger.error(`Timeout on ${url}: ${err.message}`);\n    return null;\n  });\n```<br/>Store errors and implement exponential backoff: if a page times out 3 times in a row, skip checking for 1 hour, then try again. <strong>Proxy Rotation:</strong> For large-scale checking, use rotating proxies to avoid IP bans. Services like Bright Data rotate through thousands of proxies."
